This is my design of a peristaltic pump or hose pump if you translate it directly from german.
I built this pump for reseach to gather basic hands-on knowledge of the inner workings.
If you have a MakerBot/3D Printer you can start right away. I built it in a few hours with common parts i had at hand.
Unfortunately you definitly NEED a very flexible silicone tubing, to get it really working. I did my first try with a short piece of tube i cut from our fish tank - this was definitely to hard for the ABS. unfortunately i was to eager to pump some water, so i did, but the contraption got too hot and broke.
The Pictures are from the rebuilt, but this time i'm waiting to get the silicone tube.  
Currently there are no mounting holes for a motor. i used my electric screwdriver for testing. Gearmotor is planned, but i had to determine the required torque with this build.

First off all print the parts from the attached files. While printing dismantle the Pc Fan amd harvest the ball bearings. Broken PC Fans are a great source for these. Either you remove the splint from the backside, which can be tricky, or - i prefer the hammer method - search for the upper end of the axle in the middle of the propeller. Use a center punch and a hammer and remove the axle from the propeller. the Fan will split up in its pieces.
If the fan says maglev let it be. those fans have a magnetic bearing, so nothing to harvest inside. Take the pump base and insert the 8mm ball bearing from the fan in the center hole, just as much that it's even on the inside. put it away. Take one X shaped part and screw it onto the M3x30(-40)mm bolt, add a M3 nut, one-two M3 washers and finish the stack with another M3 nut. You may tighten them.
Drill the center hole of the 2nd X Shaped part just as much so you wont have to screw it to the M3 rod. Take the blind rivets and cut thier shaft in 12mm pieces. insert them into the 4 holes on the 2nd X shaped part, using gentle force and a hammer.
Stack 2 M2 washers, one wheel and 2 M2 washers on each axle.
You can also only mount one pair of wheels or just one wheel, tis thing is made for experimentation. Put the wheels X thingie on the long M3 bolt. Match the axles as good as you can and use a gripper to press the axles in the other X part's holes.
Finish with a M3 nut. The wheels should turn, easily. if you tighten the last M3 nut and the wheels stop turning, you have to add another m3 washer in the middle. put the roller wheel into the base and fasten it with a M3 nut. Insert your tube and close the pump with the top cover and some plastic screws. As tube i ordered a silicone tube outer diameter 6mm inner 5mm. i think this will be the optimal tube for a self printed pump, that should work without electric screwdriver in the future.

comments.text:
Most computer fans have 3 wires coming out. One is a ground wire, one is a power wire, and one is a sense wire. The sense wire outputs a certain amount of pulses per revolution (2 is typical) that you can measure with a microcontroller (like the Raspberry Pi) using a digital input pin. The sense wire can also be called a tach wire (tachometer). There are some computer fans that have 4 wires... the 4th is for controlling the speed.
To control the fan speed for both 3 and 4-pin fans, you would use pulse width modulation (PWM). The R-Pi can create a PWM signal on one of its digital output pins. Here is a link explaining PWM:
http://www.embedded.com/electronics-blogs/beginner-s-corner/4023833/Introduction-to-Pulse-Width-Modulationhttp://www.embedded.com/electr...
For the 4-pin fans, you can just supply PWM directly into the control pin. Can somebody double check me on that, because I'm not sure if a 3.3v PWM from the R-Pi has high enough voltage for 5v/12v fan's onboard speed controller.
For 3-pin fans, you would have to use PWM on the power wire. However, you can't connect the PWM signal from the R-Pi directly to the power wire of the fan because 1: CPU fans don't operate on 3.3V and 2: The R-Pi digital output pins can't supply enough current to power the fan. So you will have to feed the PWM from the R-Pi into a transistor that is connected to both the fan and a strong enough voltage source. I googled around, and this gives a good example of how to use the transistor:
http://www.techpowerup.com/forums/threads/so-you-want-pwm-control-of-your-new-cpu-fan.107135/http://www.techpowerup.com/for...
You will have to do some calculations to get your transistor set up correctly, but it's not too hard. Try the concept out with an LED first, that way you don't fry your fan while you are learning :)
Once you have PWM set up, you can create a feedback loop that accurately controls the fan speed. Your R-Pi will continuously measure the actual fan speed using the fan's sense/tach pin, and then the R-Pi will continuously adjust the PWM duty cycle to make sure the fan's actual speed meets the desired speed. You can use a PID controller for this... here is a link explaining PID:
http://www.csimn.com/CSI_pages/PIDforDummies.htmlhttp://www.csimn.com/CSI_pages...
For starters, you can just trying a P controller and adjust the gain Kp:
PWMDutyCycle = (DesiredFanSpeed - ActualFanSpeed)*Kp

description.text: This remix will hold a number of hand tools, caliper, two different sizes of glue sticks and additional print heads. description.text: The least symmetrical cubic forms as described by AEH Tutton: a Pentagonal Icositetrahedron, a Tetrahedral pentagonal Dodecahedra, both with left and right forms, and a related mineral - Cuprite. See "Crystallography and Practical Crystal Measurement", AEH Tutton, Macmillan and Co. Ltd, London, 1911, Chapter XI, p. 157. and also Figures 107, 109, and 111. https://archive.org/details/crystallographyp00tuttuoft

Tutton's "Cubic System" chapter starts with the forms with most symmetry elements and ends with those with the fewest elements.  These models together with things 863463, 861532, 859902, and 858220, add models to go with Tutton's figures as an aid to understanding cubic forms.  Tutton writes clearly without using advanced mathematics.

Wireframe dome nuts. This will allow you to print hubs for geodesic domes with flexible vertrice . you will need a t least 6 long flexible and bendable wires (I used stainless steel spring wire). Start with a V1 dome (use 12x pentahub) then add as many Vs as you want with additional hexahubs. The picture here shows a 2V dome.
  • it is advised to make a little Z-shaped hook at the end so the wire doesn't come out too easily.
  • full circles link the hexagon nuts. I used thinner wire, you have to calculate the dimensions yourself. I didn't solder or glue or do anything to close the loops into circles. for what I use is it's OK, but I would definitely solder for tougher use.
  • With the given bending plan, there is only one (well, actually two since you can flip it over) way to assemble the wires
  • I made the first prototype free hand, it didn't look too great (plus it suffered a lot through the Babs-test) so I advise you take a wooden board and nail in the reference points. if possible, use straight wire (that hasn't been coiled)
  • the wire I used was a little thin in my opinion ; the thing is fun, it gets very bouncy and you can even crumple it.
    • A pretty decent dome website: http://desertdomes.com/domecalc.html please note that then lengths calculated here are based on STRAIGHT struts and therefore DO NOT MATCH the dimensions needed for the toy on the current page. Lengths for the V1 are based on solid angles ; rings for the V2 are circumferences, then for V3 onwards you will need to figure this out. If you have the formulas available, please let me know.
find some wire, set parameters, start print, bend wires, start assemble, scratch head, start again, look satisfied.

After learning about Kagome lattices at the New Magnetic Field Frontiers workshop at Ecole Physique des Houches in Les Houches in the French alps, I thought that this shape would adapt well to being a coaster.

The Kagome lattice takes its name from the weave of some baskets which originate in Japan (http://ej.iop.org/images/0953-8984/19/14/140301/kagome.gif). This geometry is used in atomic physics experiments in the form of an optical lattice to trap atoms - imagine putting an atom at each of the vertices of this shape. I built up the overall coaster in Sketchup from the base unit of a star shape, and this is in turn built up from small triangles. In V1: This was built up from 3D triangle shapes, which when put together caused all kinds of screwy faces missing, and whilst the .stl file looked okay, the gcode it produced was garbage. In V2: This was built with 2D triangles, then the entire shape was extruded as a single piece in SketchUp. This not only makes the .stl and gcode output work properly, but also makes it easier to adjust the height of the coaster in SketchUp by using the Push/Pull feature on the top face. In V3: I added a solid base to V2 in order to catch any condensation which runs off your glass - the previous versions just let this run through, which can make a mess. At 100% scale, this is around 9.6 cm by 8.3 cm - so it should be printable on even the smallest of 3D printers (e.g. the Printrbot Jr).

A nice tight fitting (console side) Nintendo 64 controller port. I build an n64 controller to PC adapter and I was using a hacked extension cable. But when I wanted to make a 4 port version I decided I should print out 4 identical ones. They don't match the actual port exactly, due to it's tiny details around the connector pins that just don't print consistently. So this modified design keeps the tight controlled fit but does require a sturdy pins to be used to make the electrical connections.  
This was hacked together in TinkerCad after measuring the actual port with a caliper. I had to make adjustments to improve useability but It was important to me that the fit be tight enough that the cable doesn't slip out.
I printed this in PLA with .3 mm layer height and 2 perimeter minimum. Print connector tab side down. Successfully printed 4 with no issues.

description.text: A 3D-printed RC car body shell in form of a bed that fits on a Tamiya TT02 chassis. Inspired by the funny creations of Edd China. Only print files that do not start with "DO_NOT_PRINT". The STL files are designed for small printers with a 15 cm (6") cube build volume. Note that printing all parts takes a long time, 33 hours on our Lulzbot Mini! We used HIPS for printing. The following files need to be printed with a brim:
  • bed-post.stl
    • The following files should be printed in high quality:
  • license-plate.stl
  • light-covers.stl
    • The following files need to be printed twice:
  • bed-side.stl
  • slot-connector.stl
    • Use only a small value of in-fill on all six mattress pieces to keep the mattress light. Beside the 3D printed parts you will need a 2 mm thick plate (acrylic, HIPS, wood ...), assorted screws, paint, glue, fabric, magnets, figure, light buckets, LEDs ... The holes for the lights are designed for the Axial light bucket set AX80045. Feel free to modify the OpenSCAD source files for other light buckets. And the ultrasonic sensor mount is longer so that it overhangs the battery case making room for the sensor's connectors beneath.

This is a basic Arduino robot platform that you can print out and use to learn basic programming and robotic skills, or use as a platform for a more practical project.   
It incorporates a rail system to slide in new parts including a AA (x6) battery pack, an ultrasonic sensor mount, and a breadboard mount, with many more planned for the future.   
Instead of re-designing the entire robot, just redesign mounts for the rails.

Building this robot. 3D Printing: We printed this out on the lowest possible resolution on a MakerBot Replicator 2. We used rafts and supports but would recommend only printing the body with supports and everything else without them in a separate print. If you have the time, of course feel free to use better resolution! You will need 2 9g micro servos converted to continuous rotation. We have a tutorial here ( http://www.makerzoo.co/converting-servos-for-continuous-rotation/ ). You will also need some 3mm bolts and nuts of various lengths. Also, some small rubber bands could be glued into the groove on the main wheels and also the caster wheels. If you prefer, using friction welding on the casters to secure the wheels in place with a piece of filament works better than nuts and bolts which come loose. We only had long 3mm bolts so we used a rotary tool and a cutting wheel to cut them off. PLEASE USE SAFETY GOGGLES WHEN DOING THIS! The main wheels now fit much better than previous versions. All you need is the screws that come with your micro servo to secure the wheel to the servo armature. The battery case and ultrasonic sensor mount need to be redesigned. We put together both and realized the soldering gets in the way when the battery holder slides onto the rail, and there is no way to access the ultrasonic sensor's pins when the batteries are in the case! Keep an eye here for the updates! Read more here: http://www.makerzoo.co/the-making-of-a-robot-kit/

comments.text: I designed something like this to take an A engine, the trick is to print the tube containing the rocket as long as possible and slide the engine to the top, while keeping the fins short and to the back. Or you could add pennies or something to the nose/make it much taller. For the rocket to be stable the center of gravity must be ahead of the center of pressure ( determined by an integral of the surface area). Basically it should be heavy toward the nose for it to be stable, minimize surface area near the front, maximize it near the back. I used six short but long fins with a thin circular ring around them, the sort of thing that would be really hard to build by hand but prints easily.  Mine flow like a missile since I printed a launch tube for it instead of using the guide-rod, no tumbling, straight flight, the rocket exhaust didn't quite burn the back of the tube although it melted a bit and may be a hazard since the exhaust is coming out of the engine part-way up the rocket body. I'll probably post it once I'm finished optimizing it, but for stability just remember to keep weight in the nose to prevent tumbling, get the fin surface area as close to the back as possible.

title: Mini Catapult - Supports for the base

description.text:
I printed this cool mini catapult by ATECH:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:438870 The result was awesome, the catapult shoots great distances with good precision, however I noticed that the thin base tends to fold up when the rubber bands are fully stretched (to achieve greater distances). I decided to add two supports on the side of the base, and I included diagonal slots on the bottom part of the rails to make room for the rubber bands, so that the whole catapult is flat on the ground. UPDATE: I designed an improved version (files marked with v2), with the sliding slots terminated on both sides so that the supports would not slide backwards after shooting. I also deepened the slots for the rubber bands, so that the catapult will rest flat on the undelying surface even if larger rubber bands re used. The catapult in the picture features my other addition, a triggering mechanism:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:865653

I printed this with 0.2mm layers, in PLA. Once printed, simply slide the two rails on the sides of the base and under the rubber bands that go round the sides, making sure the diagonal slots stay on the bottom of the catapult.
There's no need to disassemble the catapult to mount the supports,

description.text: A freestanding filament spool stand for 1Kg spools. Suitable for spools with a 50mm axle hole that are less than 70mm wide.

I printed this cool mini catapult by ATECH:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:438870 Then I designed some supports for the base, in order for it to be less flexible, and also so that the catapult could rest flat on the surface despite the rubber bands going under it:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:865607 The last thing I wanted to add was some sort of triggering mechanism, and so I designed this, taking advantage of one of the rubber bands used for shooting to also hold it into place. Once held in tension, just press down the little lever on the back and the catapult will shoot!

I printed with 0.2m layer height, in PLA.  
Once printed, just slide the trigger into the back part of the catapult's base, and hook one of the rubber bands to the protruding edge at the very end of the trigger's base.  
To shoot, pull the catapult's spoon back until it locks into the trigger, load the catapult and pull the trigger's lever back until it releases the catapult.

The Kubotan (sometimes erroneously spelled as Kubaton or Kobutan) is a genericized trademark for a self-defense keychain weapon developed by Takayuki Kubota in the 1960s. It is typically no more than 5.5 inches (13.97 centimetres) long and about half an inch (1.25 centimetres) in diameter, slightly thicker or the same size as a marker pen. The material is usually of a hard high-impact plastic (e.g. Lexan). The body of the Kubotan is lined with six round grooves with a screw eye and/or swivel and split ring attachment at one end for keys. The Kubotan may appear as an innocuous key fob to the untrained eye. In some cases however it may be recognized and considered an offensive weapon in some jurisdictions.

title: Longer legs for the Quantum Trifecta

description.text: Like most people with a Quantum Trifecta Tricopter, I needed longer legs to stop the battery hitting the ground. This is my version. The kink in the leg is to allow the leg when folded to pass over the ESCs under the leg. I don't have a 3D printer so these were sent to Shapeways for printing. This has the advantage that I don't have to worry about orientation, support material, clean up or anything like that but I do have to wait about 10 days to see the results. I have a you tube video discussing the design. https://youtu.be/G9kZP7-YGcw The 123D Design file has been included for anyone that wants to modify it for their own purposes. 1-Aug-2015 I have changed the design of the rear leg. I found the original would fold on bumpy landings so I've mad a bigger support for it but this means it doesn't fold as nicely. Check out the photos of the change.

I simply sent the STL files to Shapeways for production and let them worry about the hard stuff.  
It uses the existing thumbscrew to attach the rear leg and the push in pins for the front legs. The STL file for the front leg only contains one leg but two need to be produced.

description.text:
This is yet another extruder fan surround for a 40mm fan. This designed to maximise airflow, and allow cooling from all angles. It's also modular and easy to print (even worked on my badly calibrated printer).
EDIT: A few problems have been identified (see below) which are being worked on...

I designed this for fun when I was learning OpenSCAD, and finally made it, so thought I'd share it unfortuantely this means the SCAD file is a complete mess and the original STL output for fanTrunking(); from SCAD has holes but Netfabb (http://cloud.netfabb.com/) sorted it out.
If you're using the SCAD file, you'll need to comment out either the fanTrunking(); or the extruderSurroundPlacement(); as the extruderSurround is fairly delicate and I figure best printed separately (and they overlap and are not Z aligned).
You will probably want a fan running to reduce sagging (I wired the 40mm fan temporarily to the x-carriage while this was printing).
After printing you'll have to remove the front support to allow air in, but the inner support is optional. Regarding Melting during use: Despite surrounding the entire extruder most of the inner wall (protected by Kapton tape) was OK for a number of prints. Even when it loosened (see below) it only melted the portion in direct contact with the extruder head. This was probably for two reasons: Firstly Slic3r did something funny with the inner support wall which meant it the wall printed as blobs linked with thin trails of plastic - effectively a wall with lots of tiny holes. I think this may have been because my wall thickness was thinner than the extruded filament. However I considered this a plus and left it intact. This was lined with Kapton, but I also have quite a few layers of Kapton holding air pockets to insulate the extruder, and the top 1/2 of the fan output is directed over the x-carriage and will also assist somewhat with the cooling - if yours is properly configured then you may want to leave the supports out (play with the extruderSurroundPlacement() module) in the SCAD file.
Unfortunately the outer wall wasn't insulated by Kapton, and after sitting just over an overheated bed without the fan on, it softened and distorted, which opened unwanted air gaps and reduced the apetures. However despite this it still works OK.
I did try filling the gaps with hot-melt glue, but the bed melted it and left a liquid glue dripping all overthe bed (DUH, who would have thought!!)
Another problem was that this softened out wall was a magnet for stray flakes of ABS - if anything didn't adhere to the bed correctly the outer wall was sure to catch it and rip it off completely. Thus a bit more than the 5mm clearance I tried would be a good idea.
I now plan to make a new version with kapton inside and out, and slightly smaller to improve clearances.

description.text:
This was a bot we used to teach workshops about using an Arduino to control a walking robot.   
The robot moved only forward and backward but showed users how to wire up a joystick, power switch, batteries and servos to an Arduino and then program it all to work.

//Create two servo instances
Servo myservo;
Servo myservo1; int frontPin = 9;
int backPin = 10; //Change this numbers until the servos are centered!!!!
//In theory 90 is perfect center, but it is usually higher or lower.
int FrontBalanced = 91;
int BackCentered = 102; int angle = 25; //Variables to compensate for the back center of balance when the front shifts
int backRight = BackCentered - 10;
int backLeft = BackCentered + 10; int xPin = A4;
int yPin = A5; const int FRONT = 1;
const int BACK = 2;
const int LEFT = 3;
const int RIGHT = 4; //Setup initial conditions of the Servos and wait 2 seconds
void setup()
{
myservo1.attach(frontPin);
myservo.attach(backPin);
myservo1.write(FrontBalanced);
myservo.write(BackCentered);
// delay(5000);
Serial.begin(9600);
} void frontLeg(int x) {
myservo1.write(x);
} void backLeg(int x) {
myservo.write(x);
} void loop()
{
int x = analogRead(xPin);
int y = analogRead(yPin);
Serial.print("x :");
Serial.println(x);
Serial.print("y :");
Serial.println(y); int direction = 0;
if (x > 700) {
direction = BACK;
} else if (x < 300) {
direction = FRONT;
}
// if (y > 700) {
// direction = RIGHT;
// } else if (y < 300) {
// direction = LEFT;
// } switch (direction) {
case FRONT:
front();
break;
case BACK:
back();
break;
case LEFT:
left();
break;
case RIGHT:
right();
break;
default:
straight();
break;
}
delay(1);
} //Walking function
void front(){
frontLeg(FrontBalanced + angle);
delay(50);
backLeg(BackCentered - angle);
delay(200);
frontLeg(FrontBalanced - angle);
delay(50);
backLeg(BackCentered + angle);
delay(200);
} void back(){
backLeg(BackCentered - angle);
delay(50);
frontLeg(FrontBalanced + angle);
delay(200);
backLeg(BackCentered + angle);
delay(50);
frontLeg(FrontBalanced - angle);
delay(200);
} //Walking function
void left(){
frontLeg(FrontBalanced + angle - 5);
delay(100);
backLeg(BackCentered - angle);
delay(300);
frontLeg(FrontBalanced - angle - 5);
delay(100);
backLeg(BackCentered + angle);
delay(300);
} //Walking function
void right(){
frontLeg(FrontBalanced + angle + 5);
delay(100);
backLeg(BackCentered - angle);
delay(300);
frontLeg(FrontBalanced - angle + 5);
delay(100);
backLeg(BackCentered + angle);
delay(300);
} void straight() {
frontLeg(FrontBalanced);
backLeg(BackCentered);
}

title: Customizable Side Panel for Rostock Max v2

description.text:
This is a side panel for a SeeMeCNC Rostock Max v2 delta printer. You can use it to hide those dangling cables by adding a power module (plug) and USB panel mount cable. This example also includes venting for the power supply as well as a switch for use with accessories.  
You can modify the .scad file to add or adapt your own connectors.

If you want a full panel with holes for the default connectors (switch, power supply, USB, vent), simply print the full panel and replace the panel on the right side of the machine.  
I've also included a partial panel you can use if you don't mind cutting your existing panel. That's the option I chose, but the full panel works equally well - just takes a lot longer to print. Besides, I wanted the connectors to be recessed a bit.   
If you want the panel to be on the left, add this command to the .scad file and comment out similar calls.  
mirror(1,0,0) side_panel(full=true);  
For the connectors, I uses a salvaged US-spec male power connector, a USB panel mount with an 18" cable plugged into the electronics board, and a 6mm shaft DPST switch.  
You can route the wiring through existing holes in the frame as shown in the photos.  
To connect the power cable, cut off the wall side plug and route the wiring as shown then strip the wiring and solder it to the power plug leads. Be sure to wire it correctly!   
The exact colors of the wiring inside the power cable can vary so make sure you use a continuity tester to ensure you're wiring it correctly.   
Enjoy!

title: Filament Duck remix for thin large spools

description.text: This is another quick and dirty remix of the Filament Duck (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:143424 by Bold). This one is stretched-and-compressed to fit filament rolls that are too thin and has too large a diameter (roughly 20cm) to fit the original directly. EDIT: It turns out the thickness of these kinds of rolls differs too. Why am I surprised? UPDATE: The initial version has now been printed, and it turns out to fit a roll that is 55mm thick quite perfectly. A better fit for 68mm has been added. UPDATE june 30, 2015: A version for 82mm thick rolls has been added. Sketchup Make source is included for all versions (though if you go there I suggest starting from the original STL instead -- this can be scaled so much prettier. :-)
